{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> στέαρ</b>, τό, <br /> <i>genitive</i> στέατος [see. entry near the end]; <i>contraction</i> <b>στῆρ</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “PCair.Zen.” 703.2, 6 (3rd c.BC), 2nd c.AD: Archigenes Medicus cited in 2nd c.AD: Galenus Medicus 12.861, 2nd c.AD(?): Theodotion LXX “Bel.” 27\">LXX+3rd c.BC+</a>], <i>genitive</i> στῆτος [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “PCair.Zen.” 176.183 (3rd c.BC)\">Refs 3rd c.BC+</a>]; also <b>στεῖαρ</b>, <i>genitive</i> στείατος [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.AD: Choeroboscus Grammaticus “Scholia in Theodosii Canones” 1.350 \">Refs 4th c.AD+</a>] H.:—<b>hard fat, suet</b>, such as ruminating animals have, opposed to πιμελή (soft fat), ἐκ δὲ στέατος ἔνεικε μέγαν τροχόν a large cake of <b>suet</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 21.178; οὔτε πιμελὴν οὔτε στέαρ 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “de Partibus Animalium” 651a26; τὸ τῶν ἰχθύων σ. πιμελῶδες [prev. author] “HA” 520a21, +others \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__2</b></Level3> any <b>animal fat</b>, σ. τῆς ἄρκτου [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-3rd c.BC: Theophrastus Philosophus “de Odoribus” 63; σ. δελφίνων 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Anabasis” 5.4.28; frequently in LXX (LXX.Lev.3.15, 16, 17, +others); also “PRev.Laws” 50.14 (3rd c.BC), “PCair.Zen.” [prev. cited] \">LXX+5th c.BC+</a>]; so σ. χήνειον, ὀρνίθειον, etc., [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 1st c.AD: Dioscorides (Dioscurides) Medicus 2.76. \">Refs 1st c.AD+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__II</b></Level2> ={σταῖς} (which see), <b>dough made from flour of spelt</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Hippocrates Medicus “περὶ γυναικείης φύσιος” 27 (but σταῖς is probable reading), 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Problemata” 879a10, 4th-3rd c.BC: Theophrastus Philosophus “Historia Plantarum” 9.20.2, LXX.Psa.80(81).17, +others, 1st c.BC-1st c.AD: Strabo Geographus 17.2.5 (citing 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 2.36, where σταῖς is in our text). [Gen. στέατος _disyllable_, 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” [same place] \">LXX+8th c.BC+</a>]; στέᾱτι <i>trisyllable</i>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-3rd c.BC: Diphilus Comicus 119 \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; compare στεάτιον.] (Prob. from *στᾱ<b>y</b>αρ, cf. Sanskrit <i>styāyate</i> 'congeal, grow hard'.)","strongNumber":"G9155","accentedUnicode":"στέαρ","shortDef":"fat; fatling","mediumDef":"fat; fatling","stepGloss":"fat","stepTransliteration":"stear","count":0,"_step_Type":"word"}]}